I took the class twice at the center and took careful notes each time and I have also taken lots of the online classes XLT. < review>
Update 9/2/20. After my original review was posted, I received a call from Chris Crum, the owner of OTA KC. His voicemail said wanted to discuss my "request for a refund". I responded in writing, stating we needed written communication for both of our interest. No response after 3 weeks. Also, they disabled reviews on their Facebook page so that my review could not be seen there.

As a "Mastermind Student" (top package), I am 100% DISSATISFIED with OTA OF KC, and my "investment" into OTA has been a complete waste of time and money.
1. OTA OF KC Misrepresented the Time Investment Required
2. OTA OF KC Misrepresented Projected Income
3. OTA CORPORATE'S Training "Product" Contains Significant Amount of Conflicts in Training Instruction

1. OTA OF KC frequently cited the following before purchase: "You can set your trades and forget it. You only need a couple of hours each day. Trade anytime day or night. Most students are profitable within six months." The realities are that time investment required is substantial, and OTA trainers refuted these claims in more advanced classes from other areas that stated:
"Setting your trades and not monitoring them is a high risk for loss and not advised. Setting your trades at night and letting them run is foolish. It takes years, many hours of training, and tons of hard work to become a profitable trader. Technically you can place a trade any time of day, but doing so outside of the peak hours of 7 AM to 11 AM M-F is foolish." The few successful traders I have spoken to all have stated that it took 3-5 years to become profitable, after spending 20+ hours each week.  None of my OTA fellow students I have kept in touch with have become profitable after 20 months and substantial time investment. OTA OF KC had foreknowledge about my schedule limitations, yet never provided caution of time needed. Repeatedly, they assured me of flexibility and minimal time investment.

2. OTA OF KC projected income thru a customized "trade plan". Goals, objectives, and projections were all provided by OTA OF KC, based on their calculations. As described above, Schedule limitations were NOT taken into account when accessing "trading risks" within their plan. OTA OF KC failed to disclose "No Entry Trades" during income projections, success rates, or training. OTA's own student accessible "MYOTA" website shows their "Pro Picks" professional trade recommendations from December 27, 2018, till May 27, 2020, are as follows::
558 recommended trades
35 Closed for Break Even
50 Closed for Loss
59 Closed for Profit
414 never made an entry (74%)
No entry trades use margin and limit the number of trades you can place per day, thereby affecting your profitability. Despite "no entry trades," accounting for over 74%, OTA OF KC failed to disclose "no entries" during training, trade plan creation or projected income. This information is not common knowledge by a novice trader. When I asked for help, OTA OF KC and OTA corporate said to "watch more videos".

3. Training materials are not taught consistently between instructors, which causes SIGNIFICANT confusion to students. It is unnecessarily frustrating and leads to students' poor trading results. This problem is common knowledge among OTA staff and trainers.  Drastic and vast differences in training methods require an immeasurable amount of time for a new student to determine correctly. Making OTA's "training product" a disputable "benefit" over other far less expensive trading classes.

All items stated in this review are verifiable. A simple google search into FTC suit against OTA validates these statements and confirms OTA's long-standing practice of buying off bad reviews.

When I requested a refund, they denied it. OTA OF KC cited a three-day clause for "returns". No product this complex or this expensive is possible within that short time-frame. OTA OF KC never saught to resolve my complaints, provide solutions, or even apologize despite spending $48k with their organization. A huge regret that I hope others avoid.< /review>

For beginners, I am not associated with OTA (Online Trading Academy), nor its administration, and I am not providing this review as part of a promotional reimbursement.
My experience with OTA, its staff and instructors, has been very positive, even though I have taken classes for only two months.
My motivation for selecting OTA to lead me through the myriad paths of investing in the financial markets is multi-faceted :
1) I have a desire to proactively control how my hard-earned money is used for my retirement.
2) I have a desire to alter my old career paths into a more rewarding, and more profitable direction.
3) I need help understanding how to apply the financial resources available to me to achieve my goals.
4) I want professional, experienced, and enthusiastic guidance for embarking on my new career path, and to support me down the road when I need it.
5) I want results sooner, not later, to allow me the time to enjoy the results of my effort.

< Review>
I first attended OTA as a newbie in August and over the first three days was floored by the mass of knowledge nestled in the folds of Irvine's metropolis- knowledge that many if not all of my peers knew nothing of. I was back again in September for the ProTrader class and once again  was impressed by the professional expertise of the instructors and staff, but also the down to earth amicability that warms the otherwise A/Ced building.
Just yesterday I finished the ForEx class and now my head is full of invaluable information regarding HOW and WHY the markets work as they do.
Being the fresh outta high-schooler that I am, it was a thought provoking experience to be seated for days at a time by people who are a good ten, twenty, even fifty years older than me! The classes taught at OTA are really for anyone of any age so long as they have the dedication, interest, and learnability to really take in the cascade of knowledge. Every instructor is different- they all have different styles of teaching and trading and they respect that each and every student is an individual with their own mind and their own 'Why'.
OTA gets five stars in my reckoning because in the collective 15 days I've spent in classes their, I've learned about as much in a full semester of *normal* school; for those of you that know Plato's allegory of the Cave, it's like that.<//Review>

<Text>My 17-year-old son is very good with money.  He started selling my cookies and brownies at school when he was 12, unbeknownst to me, and continually saved the money in a drawer.  I discovered it when he was 15, asked him about the stack of cash, and realized that my boy had a really good head on his shoulders.  I wanted to encourage him to use his piggy-bank wisely and all of the future income that he will make, so I looked into different programs that would teach him about economics, the stock market, making money.  He and I went to several presentations offered by a variety of investment "schools" or money-making programs.  The one that we liked the most was OTA.  We felt that it had the most comprehensive program for us to start with.  We liked the idea of becoming MasterMind students and being part of a community of like-minded people who could encourage and mentor us for the rest of our lives - especially my teenage son.
We have attended several of OTA's week-long classes and have learned more than we had imagined.  The instructors are all very different: different personalities and different teaching styles, but their core strategies for trading and doing well in the markets are consistent and reliable as long as you don't deviate from their proven methods.  We don't want to recreate the wheel; we just want to benefit from its creation. The same with OTA: we want to be as successful as all of the teachers and mentors, who are very willing to share the stories of their success and their techniques.  So, we'll do what they teach us to do and become successful ourselves.
We are beginning to trade "live," after gaining some valuable practice from the simulated account.  The income potential is huge and we love being part of a global billion dollar industry that changes constantly. The freedom and flexibility that trading will provide for us is what I have been looking for for years. I'm leaving my 24-year legal career to do something really exciting and fun!  As for my son, he is going away to college in the fall.  People have asked us, "Why does he even need to go to school?  He's going to be really successful at trading!"  It's up to him what he wants to do -- and it's up to you to take charge of your life too.  This could be the key to your future.  I know it is for him, and it is for me.</Text>< Pics>

<user_id>118070060007066682173</user_id><user_name>Ms. Mage</user_name><time>1557631214123<//time><rate>5</rate><review>I've been to Andrews brunch over 20 times by this point. I'm loving this new spot and his menus never disappoint.
Seasonal menus, well thought out, locally sourced, quality products cooked to a holy perfection.
Eggs Stinson is maybe a all time favorite but Eggs Hemingway is stealing my heart.
11AM menus are cheaper but less food and DELICIOUS.
1PM meals are more expensive but 100% worth it. You will have to roll home because you will not be able to walk.
Definitely come on time or early. This is a family style dining experience and coming late means risking missing courses.
Parking is rough in this area, so carpool or Bart if you can.
God bless you, Andrew.<//review>< pictures>

<pictures>[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPBVSLlzvjeLT-Nu0Xa3VolHtXEtRxh6H2B1J1N=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNIEaeQbIoPMlRLFxTweBxWz_14UZ6qNTqGIOy9=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMTTIz_jqFuXqRfh7VKKWMhlThXxcT6k8xDXdR3=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipNroQO8R2yrM5yml-GunydDq9QPEeMgJGbHDK7g=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</pictures>< rate>
4</rate>
< Text>
A very cool pop-up that my friends enjoyed more than I did (we had the late brunch). Still, highly recommended!
Let's dig in and start with "The good" -
* Food and ingredients are superb. It is, after all, the chef Andrew McCormack from Quince and Spruce so expect a very high quality
* The atmosphere - The place is relatively small and the sitting is around shared tables ("family-style"). It's nice and makes the whole thing feels very cozy; however, that does affect the conversation at the table.
* The tomatoes - Not kidding. You haven't tried anything like it.
* The smoked salmon schmear - Just crack. It's impossible to stop eating this stuff
* And the best part - If you need seconds, just ask. But don't do it - There is so... much... food! You won't leave hungry.

Now to the "Not So Good"
* Remember the tomatoes I've mentioned earlier? They are delicious, but completely took over the taste for the main dish (Eggs Blackstone). They were so sweet and flavorful that I couldn't taste anything but the tomato. We were four people, and I'm the only one who felt this way, so take that with a grain of salt (hah!)
* The service was ok but not "amazing." Two people were serving the whole room, which might be not enough. I'm not blaming the staff, they were running around but that what caused some of the mess (eggs were broken, water was spilled)
* The price. For a brunch - It's very $$$$ (about $200 including tip for four, no mimosas). For brunch from chef Andrew McCormack - That's fine.

Tips -
Make a reservation!</Text>

< text>
We found this spot accidentally strolling by and scheduling a brunch there every weekend ever since.

The meal itself is great - pancakes, sausage, scramble eggs - everything is superb. But there is also short, but quite distinct selection of drinks (which makes a real weekend brunch, you know), including awesome French biodynamics sparkling wine.

Staff is super nice and friendly and creates a vibe of having a breakfast in some friend's house. Who happen to be high-level chef...

Awesome experience altogether.<//text>

< text>
If you have never been to a communal food event and if you don't want to wait in line for some mediocre brunch in SF, well, give this event a try! I bet you will not regret it. I have done 5-6 Feastly(communal food) events in the past, but I think this is the best one over all. The food is amazing, and you get SO MUCH FOOD! The service, the people you meet and atmosphere is great, and the price is just right too. Maybe, with all the food you get, I would actually say that it's on the cheaper side. I don't really like brunch usually, but "Early to Rise" is my exception :) Highly recommend!<//text>

<gmapID>0x8085812462b10ff3:0xcba731b9d6a6d184<//gmapID></record>
</dataset><record>
<text>You can taste the hospitality, love, and care in Chef Andrew's food. The place is cute, bright, and the staff chirpy and receptive. This entire experience from beginning to end, feels like coming into an adorable home, sitting with new friends and old, and sharing a meal. You're lost in time. It's a beautiful way to spend a Saturday afternoon. Totally an escape from San Francisco.

We were here for my husband's birthday in June 2019 and then again this past saturday for a friend's 30th. There were other celebrations taking place, including a bridal shower. It felt like everyone contributed to the fun atmosphere, but yet had their own private parties. It wasn't too loud, but also wasn't quiet. This is a great, intimate place to come as one, two, or 20. The last time we came, we sat next to a couple who have now become friends. Take care of each other and pass the plates around, and feel comfortable asking for someone to pass a dish not in front of you. There's plenty to go around. It all really flows naturally. (Caveat: if you're looking for an incredibly intimate, quiet spot, and don't want to talk to other people-- this is not the place to come)

The food: previously, the star of the show was the apricot french toast, and this time Shrimp and Grits. Chef Andrew's from the South so this was close to his heart, and you could tell. There was homemade hot sauce that I wish I could buy by the bottle. The bagels and lox are dangerous, because you want to keep going, but know there's so much more food coming. The succotash was fresh and a nice complement to the rest of the meal. We were also surprised with homemade maple sugar beignets because Chef Andrew recently got a donut fryer, so you know, why not spoil us with his creativity. His passion to feed is very much welcomed and appreciated. We look forward to next time.< /text><Rating>5<//Rating>< response>
{'time': 1579280110394, 'text': "You're the best, Jasleen! Thanks for taking the time to tell everyone about your meal. Hope you are well!\n\nBest,\n\nAndrew"}<//response>

It's been a crazy year and we've had to pivot so many times it's been difficult to find our feet again.\n\nThat said, I was hoping to get some more details about how your experience went awry. I saw your review in the middle of service, and immediately tried the coffee and also talked to other customers to see if there was an issue. I felt it was a bit extracted for my tastes and instructed the staff to coursen the grind a bit, but we had no negative feedback from other customers. That's a bit of a mystery but I'll keep an eye on it. Our coffee is roasted by Highwire Coffee Roasters in Oakland every week and mailed directly to us. All of our recipes are refined with feedback from our customers so whatever details you can provide would go a long way toward making sure our future guests have a better experience. <user_id>105735232414938334658< /user_id><user_name>Cheyne Koster</user_name><Date>1614120290098<//Date>< Rating>
5</Rating>
< text>
AWESOME SANDWICH PLACE! Kind of a tucked away gem, didn't think Google maps was directing me correctly. Anyways, great sandwich place to have a bite, there affordable and have a HUGE menu and it's not just sandwiches either. They have burgers, burritos numerous different types of food. Don't let the name fool you not only sandwiches! Definitely worth a try, great prices considering the portions are generous and so are the owners. Can't say enough good things and there macaroni salad is fantastic. My wife doesn't even like macaroni salad but everytime we eat here she gets it as a side, sometimes even gets an extra side to take home. That says something right there! They also have a good potato salad/sides options and everything else you would expect at a good sandwich shop. You can also order ahead for pick up if in a hurry or anything else. Grab a togo menu when your there, bc it's extensive and you will always be able to find something new the next time you go, see if you can work through the whole menu sometime, lol. Anyways great little sandwich, lunch, early dinner gem tucked away. Worth the visit!< /text>

Ok so I have waited to do this rating AGAIN. Hyde's is a very good company BUT there are lots of very good air-conditioning companies.
They will tell you OVER and OVER how they really care about customer service.. But so does everyone else and every where you go. The difference is IF a company delivers on great company service. For Hydes I would say NO ! Did they do a good job in selling  (yes) did they do a good job installing (yes) but all the little things the things that are important to ME and i would assume other they FAILED. Examples when they did my instal they never replaced my air filters. When I asked why they said they should have‚Ä¶ But NEVER sent someone over to take care of it. Only when they had to come to complete inspection PRIOR to the city coming and I complained again and they sent someone over. Well they had the wrong size. SO they replaced on (of three) I happen to find an old one in my garage so they used that. But the third one they did not have. So they wanted to bend one in half and put that in there. I said NO . Now GREAT customer service would mean the next day TODAY they would be here with a new one to replace it (or at least call me to set an appointment) Nothing. The city has to come to sign off on final permit so they told me the city would be here today. and the city would call me in the morning. I told Hydes I would be out in the morning and back at 10 am. Hyde's said well you can call the city and tell them that. GREAT customer service would have said what time would you like them there and I will work with the city to try to meet your time. NOT offered.
The final item that really upset me today is the city came and had to go up to the attic area. When they lifted up the access door it seems Hydes maintenance person painted it closed so it chipped when they pushed on. That is when I noticed that when Hydes first came to do the job it had a frame around the inside of the panel to hide any areas that did not sit properly. They never replaced it back to how it was before they started. Again GREAT customer service would have taken pictures and made sure it was done the way it was prior to the start. (see Photo) so are the well priced YES are the quick YES did they do good work (it works and is better then my old one) would I say they have great or even good customer service NO even though they will tell you HOW IMPORTANT it is over and over again. To do it is more then saying it. Now I have to start the conversation with them to fix this. I'll report back how that goes.
Just honest feedback and info for those who care to read it.< /text>

< review>
After purchasing a home in Palm Springs, we called Hyde's for maintenance of the AC system, which the company had installed about 2 1/2 years ago.  The $149 a year maintenance package seemed reasonable to me, and it was a simple process to set up an appointment.  The lady who helped me on the phone was very friendly and knowledgeable.  Then the appointment arrived, and Casey was early and ready to go on a hot afternoon.  He navigated the floor and room renovations that a were going on in the house, working around the crew with ease.  From first conversation with him, I knew we were in good hands.  Casey took his time , changed out filters, checked ducts, and drainage pipes, all the while explaining things to me in easy-to-understand terms.  We also asked about options to help distribute the air more evenly throughout the house, and he explained considerations in clear, honest communication.  I like that he detailed the benefits of each option.  Anyway, we decided to go with zone cooling but decided a few days later to cancel because we entered a solar panel agreement with a company that we had been considering for quite some time.  Then the more we thought about it, we think a mini-split would serve our purposes better, and we can find one much cheaper.  (The desert experience is all new to us. ..so our heads have been "swimming" with options.)  Anyway, the Hyde's representative was nice and very understanding when I called to cancel.  (By the way, they wanted $500 for move three ducts, and I ended up getting a handyman to do it for $90.)  I will stick with them for the maintenance but will continue to explore other options.  Very nice people all the way around!<//review>

<review>The technician was on time and seemed pleasant. I liked the detail of wearing protective paper booties over his shoes. At first, I thought it was nice that he asked for a broom to clean up the mess of lint and dust he made in my hallway although perhaps that's something he should carry with him. It took me awhile to find my dustpan and broom and when I finally did he'd already picked it up by hand and tossed it on my front patio. That was weird and unprofessional. He could have asked to throw it in the trash. I had to pick it up from my patio.

As for the work, it was a summer service only. He said everything checked out good except we were low on freon which meant we have a leak. He said we need to pay for a $385 leak check. That's a bit expensive so we said we'd reach out to our home warranty insurance company. He said ok and that the leak was all that needed to be done. Once he left and provided the inspection report, we saw it says there is something called a superheat which came up as "Red- requires attention/failed". I don't know what this is and if it's a problem. The word failed insinuates a problem, but because he didn't mention it I just don't know.

Overall, we joined their maintenance plan today with this service and I'm thinking maybe it wasn't a good idea. We will see.

Well fast forward to May 21st and my warranty company inspected my unit and says there is no sign of a leak, freon levels are normal and unit is functioning well. That was an unnecessary $80 copay but at least I didn't pay Hyde's $385. Not happy. Will cancel service plan after fall inspection.

Nov 16. Just had fall inspection.  Technician was nice.  Good experience.  Happy with service today.  I've increased my stars to 3 based on today's experience.  I like having someone come out and service the equipment but the first technician in the spring kind of put me off.< /review>< user_name>

< review>
Service on our A/C System.
We had our system installed by Hydes in 2015, and it has been working well, I like the notification by e-mail and text that Hydes gives for the Service Call, they even tell you the technicians name. The technician was very polite and put shoe covers on before he entered the house, he asked how the system was working, it had not been as efficient recently, and I was hoping the service would correct this.
He carried out the service, changed the filters, ran a diagnostic check on the main panel and cleaned the outside unit. He said he could not find anything significant that would have reduced the performance of the system and asked that we keep an eye on it and if it was still not working properly then to make a service call.
Technician was clean/polite and efficient, the only reason that I did not give 5 stars was that after the diagnostic check, it had stopped the wireless part of the system working, so I had to reboot the panel to get the wireless working again, no biggy, but I am glad I checked though as if we had been away from property I could not have remotely accessed system.<//review>

<userid>101504002808100852862</userid>< name>
Ron Fitzpatrick< /name>
< date>
1498764835847</date>
< Rate>
2<//Rate>
< review>
Pleasant, cordial, and professional telephone etiquette when making appointments, and when providing reminders, etc. Technicians also are very professional and courteous and "seemingly" efficient while servicing our A/C  System(s). The score I am submitting has more to do with my questioning the competence, professionalism, and followup as related to my recent experience with this company which until now I considered reliable and responsible.

After Hydes' bi-annual servicing per our contract agreement, I reported a "new noise" very audible around one of the return air ducts.  Hydes was informed of the issue and advised that the return appointment would be for late afternoon the following day. A different technician arrived, and agreed that there was an unusual "whining" noise. The technician's explanation was that the newly installed  filter as part of the servicing, was creating a "metallic" interaction with the metal grill; that this can be a normal occurrence, is not that unusual; and that he would return the next day to install an "adhesive" border/band around the opening which is the normal procedure and which would solve the problem.

The technician did not return the following day so growing a little "tired" of hearing this whining throughout the day, I decided to simply replace the filter with one of my own. The noise immediately went away.  While replacing the filter however, I discovered that rather than insert the filter in the recessed part of the grill designed for that purpose,  the filter was forced in above the recess into the larger actual duct opening.  Pieces of rubber/foam wedges (apparently pieces of rubberized piping insulation) had been placed around the edges of the filter to make it fit the opening, the result of which was a more pronounced continuation of the whining noise we were experiencing. This was the approach of the second Hydes technician in an attempt to quell the noise.

Even I am aware that the recess is designed to fit the exact size of the intended filter and does not require rubber wedges,  nor does it require an advanced degree to see or at least figure out the obvious. Quite baffling to say the least, not to mention my disappointment at the lack of efficiency and heretofore perceived competence of Hydes' technical staff.

Hydes otherwise has been quite prompt, courteous and professional in their demeanor.  I am just not sure why this happened particularly while performing such a basic procedure as changing out filters.  Two days later and no word from Hydes.  The technician still has not returned nor bothered to make contact to explain why, apologize, or to reschedule.

After several years of annual service contracts with Hydes, should I now be forced to lower my expectations or just not renew what I thought was a "professional services" contractual arrangement?</review>

<Date>1591835981059</Date><Rate>5</Rate><Text>- Hyde's Air Conditioning. 01/03/2020

Simply the Best !

The 2nd of our bi-annual service check up went without a hitch. Not only great peace-of-mind, but extends my warranty. Paying monthly locks me in from any future price increases too.

May, 2018

Top-of-the-line HVAC for the price of a basic level

As our desert temperatures rise now in May, I am so grateful we addressed our HVAC problems in February.

While I can agree with others who have said any brand of HVAC equipment properly installed and maintained will provide excellent service.  My research proved, however, there is a difference ‚Ä¶

Comparing cost, unit efficiency, and features, here is my story.

A $2,700 estimate to repair my existing system seemed like a bad investment as so far, the 7-year old 13-seer system has  required $900 in repairs and replacement parts.  The furnace has been trouble-free despite its 22 year age.   To that end, I solicited prices on an entire HVAC system, Furnace and A/C with equipment from American Standard, Carrier, Lennox and York from several desert vendors, including one displaying at our area membership warehouse.  All were first class in their representation of their products, but one company and one vendor stood out.

HYDES and AMERICAN STANDARD

For the price of a low-end Lennox system via Costco, I was able to acquire a HIGH-END, HIGH-EFFECIENCY model superior to anything the others provide.

Although American Standard is commonly associated with bathroom fittings, a corporate break-up in 2007 resulted in the selling of their plumbing division and a corporate name change to TRANE, who produce HVAC systems under both Trane and American Standard.  You may also be familiar with their parent company Ingersoll-Rand.

American Standard ‚Äì better warranty 12 year compressor

HYDES provides Parts AND Labor for 10 YEARS with their bi-annual maintenance contract.  A typical 2 hour service call would far exceed the maintenance subscription.

On offer was a Zero percent financing option for 36 months making this deal extremely attractive.

Unbelievably QUIET with variable speed compressor, variable speed outdoor condenser fan and variable speed indoor blower.  Talk about COMFORT !

Some local firms have Climate System Representatives who are sales people that evaluate and provide estimates.  HYDES sends out a technician and follow up is provided by company owner, Mike Hyde, who along with his brothers  operate an extremely well-run family organization providing 5-Star Customer Service.  Not surprising that so many of their employees have worked there for years.

A MILLION THANKS, MIKE and to ALL THE CREW AT HYDES.<//Text>< pics>

< review>
The technician was prompt and got to work checking out the A/C system to make sure it was working correctly and to determine if there were any potential problems.  He was thorough  and experienced.  After his lengthy maintenance check, all of the system were working properly.  He explained what he did, such as checking the system for leaks, etc and everything was great.  A couple years ago, the A/C went out in the summer.  Needed someone quick because of my tropical fish, so I picked Hyde from the internet.  That serviceman came within a couple hours and fixed the burned out condenser or capacitor or whatever.  Been working like a charm ever since.  So I chose Hyde to do anymore work if needed.  About a year ago, I had a problem with the A/C.  Apparently the builder put in a 10" intake ducting.  It eventually collapsed.  Hyde came out and found that the builders from Lennar put in the wrong size intake duct.  Should have been 12" diameter.  Hyde came out and replaced it with the proper size.  It was a big, heavy, insulated and awkward piece to drag up into the attic but the technicians did it and solved that problem.  But too bad the warranty ran out from Lennar but it was worth the cost to have it done right.  Got a heating/AC problem.  Call Hyde.< /review>

It was 109 degrees outside yesterday when our A/C stopped working. In a panic, we called Hydes A/C and spoke with a cheerful CSR named Janelle. She quickly set up an inspection & within 2 hours a really nice tech named Jeff Sproul showed up at our door eager to help. Fearful of having to come up with the cash to afford a brand new A/C unit, Jeff quickly diagnosed our problem - just a broken fan motor. The news got even better when he said he had a new one in his truck. Bam, done deal! Within 30 minutes, he had that baby installed and the cool air was flowing! At the time, the temp inside our home was 86 and rising, so their quick, efficient service  literally saved our lives!  Thank you Hydes for exceeding all our expectations!
